WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.660
Hey there, welcome to the Paws at Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:22.020
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12pm US Eastern Time. If

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:27.260
you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:35.700
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:41.340
Can't wait to see you there. I'm really excited to introduce our featured leader today. It's

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:47.380
Chris Gates, Director of the Bioinformatics Core at University of Michigan. Chris, it's

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:51.060
so nice to have you here today. I would love it if you could introduce yourself, tell us

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:57.220
a little bit about what you do, and I will also ask you what you like to do for fun.

00:00:57.220 --> 00:01:06.019
That's great. Thank you, Libby. It's great to be here. So yeah, I work at the Bioinformatics

00:01:06.019 --> 00:01:12.500
Core at the University of Michigan. Let me just explain that. Bioinformatics means different

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:21.739
things to different people, so it's useful to unpack that a little bit. For us, bioinformatics

00:01:21.739 --> 00:01:27.139
lives at the intersection of three different domains. One is molecular biology, which you

00:01:27.139 --> 00:01:37.739
can think of for our purposes as DNA, genes, proteins, but also statistics, and finally

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:44.900
computer science and software engineering, where those two overlap, AI now. Really, what

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:50.739
we do at the Bioinformatics Core is that we work with biological researchers, and they

00:01:50.739 --> 00:01:57.419
come to us with sequence data or proteomics data, and we help them identify patterns in

00:01:57.419 --> 00:02:05.300
DNA, then try to help them interpret what those patterns mean. So we do that a couple

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:13.940
different ways. One way is that the algorithms that people use to analyze DNA are constantly

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:19.860
changing, so we're always hip-deep in literature review to try to figure out what the best

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:25.460
practices are and apply those and also share those out to the research community. Another

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:32.460
way that we help people is that we have a series of workshops that are focused on bioinformatic

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:38.259
analysis, and the deal there is that a lot of bioinformaticians, they might have some

00:02:38.259 --> 00:02:45.139
computational chops, but it's a steep learning curve, so we try to give them an intro to

00:02:45.139 --> 00:02:49.899
some of the basics there so they have more independence. Then the final way we help them

00:02:49.899 --> 00:02:56.899
out is that we will do analyses on their behalf, and that happens a lot because biologists

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:02.179
come to us and they have a deep expertise in their domain, so they really know a lot

00:03:02.179 --> 00:03:11.339
about diabetes or the human retina or adenocarcinoma, but they don't necessarily know all of the

00:03:11.339 --> 00:03:20.059
idiosyncrasies behind the informatics and all of, frankly, kind of strange data types

00:03:20.059 --> 00:03:28.339
and algorithms that can be a little bit wonky, and even if all those things work, they typically

00:03:28.339 --> 00:03:35.020
don't have the deeper training in how do you wire this up and execute it at scale in a

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:44.619
computational reproducible way, so we help them with that.

00:03:44.619 --> 00:03:49.820
I think that's probably raised a few questions just by itself, but that was a two-parter,

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:50.820
absolutely.

