groups and venues, but around last Thanksgiving, it's a long story, but the short version is

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:15.420
somebody turned me on to steel pans, steel drums, sometimes people call them, and my wife and I

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:21.339
just kind of went all in, and so now we have these three steel drums in our house, and

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:31.339
whenever I can get any time at all, I'm on that steel drum and practicing, and now we're actually

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:35.899
going to perform in an open mic coming up in a couple of weeks, so it really got away from us,

00:05:35.899 --> 00:05:40.220
but it's super fun. Yeah, so that's what I do.

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:44.540
Music gets away from you. It's a very good thing. Your house is probably very,

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:50.459
very fun all the time. I am married to a drummer, and so I know the noise and chaos and fun that

00:05:50.459 --> 00:05:57.579
comes with that. Okay, well, we have a couple of questions in the Slido, and hilariously,

00:05:57.579 --> 00:06:02.940
they're both from Noor. Noor always gets us started with the best questions, so I will

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:09.019
highlight one of Noor's questions and stick it in the chat here, and if we could have

00:06:09.019 --> 00:06:11.899
Noor unmute and ask this question, that'd be amazing. Hey, Noor.

00:06:12.859 --> 00:06:22.220
Hi, my name is Noor. I'm also a bioinformatician. You've got to keep me honest. I also understand the

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:28.059
dilemma we often have of explaining what we do. I often say it's like, I'm like a biological

00:06:28.059 --> 00:06:33.579
data scientist, until I talk to other bioinformaticians. They're like, hi, I don't do protein. I

00:06:35.019 --> 00:06:41.660
thought it was kind of boring, so yeah, that's on me. I'm a microbial genomic,

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:47.420
like microbiome and stuff, so that's my gen, but everyone's like humans, and I'm like,

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:54.779
I guess I'll do them, but anyway, the question that I have or I'm allowed to ask, at least,

00:06:54.779 --> 00:07:01.660
is that my dream job is actually your job. How did you sort of get into that avenue,

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:06.140
or how do you basically go to the university and be like, hi, I would like to just touch

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:12.859
all your data and help you, and I'll do it for a reasonable, cheap fee, essentially, or hire me,

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:20.779
but yeah, how did you get along that avenue, per se? Yeah, that's a great question. I said

00:07:20.779 --> 00:07:25.339
at the outset, there's the notion that bioinformatics sits at the intersection of molecular

00:07:25.339 --> 00:07:30.700
biology and statistics and computer science and software engineering, and I feel like that's a

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:38.059
useful kind of paradigm, if you imagine that three-circle Venn diagram, that in general,

00:07:38.619 --> 00:07:44.940
not a lot of bioinformaticians just kind of emerge from the center of that Venn diagram.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:49.579
What they do is they come in, and a lot of times, bioinformaticians will come in from the biology

00:07:49.579 --> 00:07:55.019
side, so that they're on the bench, they're working, they're running experiments, and then

00:07:55.019 --> 00:07:59.179
at a certain point, they start getting involved in some of the analysis, and that just kind of

00:07:59.179 --> 00:08:04.380
continues to build, to a point where they're like, I would rather be working on the computer

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:08.540
than working on the bench, but that's not the only way to get there. There are people that

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:14.140
are coming in from the stats side. I personally actually came in from the software engineering

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:23.660
side, which is, it is not a well-traveled trailhead, but yeah, the short version of this

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:30.459
is that in 2007, I hooked up with a biotech. It was building a giant data mining platform based on

00:08:30.459 --> 00:08:37.900
microarray data, and I just kind of got the bug for the molecular biology. I couldn't get enough

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:43.820
molecular biology, and I was a trade software engineer at the time, and they were like, why

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:50.059
do you care about this stuff? I'm like, I don't know, but it's so amazing, isn't it? It really is

00:08:50.059 --> 00:08:57.979
this really rich, deep, complex domain. At the time, I remember a guy explaining to me,

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:08.219
he was trying to explain a concept that has to do with how the body translates DNA into

00:09:08.219 --> 00:09:17.580
individual genes. This is called translation. He was explaining this, and he kept getting

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:21.099
into more and more detail. At a certain point, I just stopped him and said, Dan,

00:09:21.739 --> 00:09:28.299
that cannot possibly be the way it works. It's just too complicated. He smiled at me,

00:09:28.299 --> 00:09:33.900
he was really nice. He was like, Chris, it's not optimising for you to be able to understand it.

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:41.340
It's this way because it makes more. That's the only reason this works. That was scary to me.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:49.260
It was like, oh, this is turtles all the way down. I might never understand this.

00:09:51.419 --> 00:10:00.539
I've spent the last 17 years trying to pick up all the molecular biology that I didn't start out

00:10:00.539 --> 00:10:11.099
with. I think that you also, in your question, hinted at a problem that I have in a bioinformatics

00:10:11.099 --> 00:10:18.299
core inside of a university, inside of an academic research institution, which is that

00:10:19.739 --> 00:10:28.059
researchers don't have any money. They can't really afford to pay you a lot of money to do

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:36.780
the analysis. But there are these circling biotechs and pharmaceuticals all around me

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:43.179
that are looking at my staff and saying, wow, we could really use that expertise.

00:10:44.219 --> 00:10:47.820
So that's scary. I have to do a lot of jazz hands with my staff and just be like, hey,

00:10:47.820 --> 00:10:53.580
look over here, isn't it fun to work here? I'm mostly successful with that.

00:10:53.979 --> 00:10:58.539
But it's a tricky problem because, again, a lot of the stuff that they're doing here,

00:10:58.539 --> 00:11:04.859
they could be doing in a biotech or a big pharma, and that has a different benefits profile.

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:10.859
I won't say anything more about that. But does that actually answer your question, Noor?

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:16.700
Kind of, kind of. You wanted the front door. Send an email here.

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:23.500
No, I'll say one more thing then, which is, you're already a bioinformatician,

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:30.299
though, so you know this. But those three circles of biology and statistics and computer science,

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:38.140
wherever you are, keep building those out. To feel really comfortable in that center,

00:11:39.659 --> 00:11:43.900
you're going to have to lean into these other spots at a moment's notice.

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:48.539
I think that's good advice, and I think this leans right into another question in Slido that's

00:11:48.539 --> 00:11:53.580
anonymous, and it says, since bioinformatics is the intersection of three highly complex fields,

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:58.219
how do you balance continued education and professional development with all three? So

00:11:58.219 --> 00:12:02.859
if the suggestion is like, keep going with all three, get to that center of the overlapping

00:12:02.859 --> 00:12:08.859
Venn diagram that looks like a little pie piece, do you have any tips on how you do that? How do

00:12:08.859 --> 00:12:14.619
you stay in that zone? Although, I think one of the answers is that you have spent over a decade

00:12:15.419 --> 00:12:25.340
doing that. Yes, I have. I think that is also a really good question, because one of the kind of

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:31.900
false aspects of this metaphor that I just drew with my hands with the three overlapping circles

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:36.219
is that those circles are actually the center of the overlapping Venn diagram.

00:12:37.179 --> 00:12:42.780
The way I draw them and the way you imagine them, they're very static, and they're very

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:48.460
kind of regular shapes. In real life, they are not regular shapes. They are like this bubbly,

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:56.299
effervescent mess. Balancing in the center, it's not a flat surface. You're always having

00:12:56.299 --> 00:13:03.020
to maintain the balance in the center of those three. I will tell you that in the last couple

00:13:03.179 --> 00:13:12.059
years, we have had a couple of interesting shocks to the system. I'll just tell you one.

00:13:14.619 --> 00:13:22.460
To do this kind of analysis at scale, an important thing that we have to do is we have to put all the

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:29.500
analyses in some kind of an automated workflow automation system, like Snakemake or Nextflow.

00:13:30.299 --> 00:13:35.739
If you're not familiar with those, those are very cool tools. We started with Snakemake,

00:13:35.739 --> 00:13:42.700
and then the Nextflow kind of community of developers, they kind of eclipsed the offerings

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:48.299
in Snakemake. We said, okay, well, we kind of have to transition to Snakemake, or sorry,

00:13:48.299 --> 00:13:53.179
we have to transition to Nextflow. That meant we had to learn a whole new workflow automation system,

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:56.780
which, I don't know, the first one's the hardest, but that was a challenge.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:06.299
I think you're right in pointing out that this is a dynamic balance that you have to attend.

00:14:07.099 --> 00:14:11.979
If you want to master something, I would recommend ancient Latin or ancient Greek.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:18.380
Bioinformatics is not that. You're always one meeting away from looking kind of ignorant about

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:23.419
something. That's the trade-off. It's like, do you want to look smart, or do you want to learn

00:14:23.419 --> 00:14:30.700
something? If you're okay sacrificing the looking smart part, you can learn a ton at every consultation

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:37.659
that we have. That's what's happening. I'll also say that the diversity of the projects that we get

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:43.900
are constantly kind of testing where we should go next. Sometimes it's like, oh, well,

00:14:44.539 --> 00:14:50.460
like right now, I don't want to get into the details, because it's going to be,

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:56.059
I mean, you'll like it, but we support a lot of different sequencing platforms.

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:02.059
The sequencing platforms themselves keep changing. There's a new sequencing platform that we're

00:15:02.059 --> 00:15:10.539
standing up right now called Ultima Genomics. The problem is that they generate such large

00:15:10.539 --> 00:15:15.419
volumes of data that we have to use our GPU high-performance clusters.

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:23.500
We're so on the edge of what they're able to do that the techs at Ultima Genomics cannot

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:31.500
fully answer the questions that we're putting to them. Now we've got to learn how GPUs are

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:36.219
being allocated on this high-performance cluster. Anyway, yeah, it is a constant

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:43.340
balance across what you're learning. Fortunately, I live in a domain where the consultations are

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:49.179
always pushing me to the edge all the time. Yeah, that's the best I could do, I think,

00:15:49.179 --> 00:15:51.820
for that. It's a great question. Thank you. Yeah, it is a great question.

00:15:53.179 --> 00:15:58.380
The talk about Venn diagrams always reminds me of Drew Conway's diagram of data science,

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:02.299
which is another thing that I feel like nobody's ever going to fully achieve. I'll put that in the

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:10.299
chat if you haven't seen it. It's computer science, math and statistics, and domain expertise. It's

00:16:10.299 --> 00:16:15.820
so hard to live in the very, very middle of that Venn diagram. I don't know if it's worth

00:16:16.619 --> 00:16:21.739
striving to fully get to the center of either of these Venn diagrams because you will never,

00:16:21.739 --> 00:16:26.059
ever know everything. Just like Chris just said, there will always be something new.

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:32.059
Even if you lived in that very, very center of the data science Venn diagram two years ago,

00:16:32.059 --> 00:16:38.619
then AI came on the scene and you had instantly more to learn that you never would have really

00:16:38.619 --> 00:16:45.260
had to learn before. Just be nice to yourself. Okay, so fantastic question, anonymous asker.

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:52.059
Thank you so much for asking. We had one from Natasha Lang, which is fantastic. It has a little

00:16:52.059 --> 00:16:57.020
asterisk, so I'll ask it for you, Natasha. It says, what does a typical day look like for you, Chris?

00:16:57.179 --> 00:16:58.140
Typical week?

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:05.500
Yeah, typical week. Typical day is, there's no such thing as a typical day for me. I actually

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:13.020
am the director of the core, so I don't get to do nearly as much analysis as I would love to do.

00:17:13.020 --> 00:17:19.900
The people working at the core are actually doing a lot of the analyses. I'm going to create a

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:30.219
fictional entity that's a blend of me and the analysts, but in a typical day, or a typical

00:17:30.219 --> 00:17:36.459
week, I'll say, we're going to be meeting with biologists who are coming to us basically with

00:17:36.459 --> 00:17:43.979
a research question and saying, hey, we're interested in understanding how genes are

00:17:43.979 --> 00:17:55.739
expressed when you have retinal diabetes. How are the genes different, retinal diabetes?

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:03.579
Are those genes different in a way where we could actually start to use that information to

00:18:03.579 --> 00:18:08.380
recommend an intervention? You should have VEGF therapy, or you shouldn't have VEGF therapy.

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:14.780
They'll articulate that question, and it's nice when they come to us before they've submitted

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:20.140
the samples, because we can guide them and say, oh, you're going to need more samples,

00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:24.619
or you're going to need this kind of sequencing. But sometimes, they just show up with the data

00:18:24.619 --> 00:18:27.979
in their pocket, and they say, we thought we were going to get an answer, and what we got

00:18:27.979 --> 00:18:35.900
was a bunch of data. Then we'll create a project plan, which actually, to a lot of researchers,

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:40.540
is kind of an alien thing, like the idea of a project plan that articulates an analysis.

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:45.660
They thought we were just going to go off and do it while they were on the call,

00:18:46.300 --> 00:18:55.660
which doesn't typically happen. Then another huge part of the week is running the code,

00:18:55.660 --> 00:19:01.020
building the pipelines, kind of shepherding the data as it moves through the different

00:19:01.819 --> 00:19:09.020
compute systems that we have, and then trying to interpret the results.

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:17.260
Interpreting the results is actually difficult, in a way, because first off,

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:22.140
the data are complicated, the tools are complicated, the visualizations can be complicated,

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:28.859
and also, under all of this, the researchers are coming to us with novel ideas. They're running

00:19:28.859 --> 00:19:35.979
things that generally haven't been done before, so it can sometimes be a little bit elusive.

00:19:35.979 --> 00:19:40.939
You can't just be like, oh, that looks like this other dataset, because there is no other precedent

00:19:40.939 --> 00:19:46.060
for that particular analysis. That said, a lot of what we're looking at,

00:19:47.420 --> 00:19:51.579
we kind of understand the informatics, we understand how the genes work, we understand

00:19:51.579 --> 00:19:56.459
how the sequencing platforms work, so we can kind of look at it with a cup of coffee in our hand

00:19:56.459 --> 00:20:00.699
and say, that looks about right. I think that what we're seeing here is important.

00:20:01.339 --> 00:20:06.060
But then, I think one of the most important meetings that we have is when we come back

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:11.500
together with the researcher, and we kind of go through this and say, we think we're seeing this,

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:17.339
but what are you seeing? That's a really tricky part of this kind of engagement model, because

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:22.060
we have the expertise in the informatics, but they have the expertise in the domain.

00:20:22.060 --> 00:20:25.979
They really understand the disease, or they understand the biology in a way that we won't.

00:20:26.619 --> 00:20:34.540
So, kind of being able to lean into that and try to pull out the actual knowledge from these

00:20:34.540 --> 00:20:39.420
visualizations and that information, that's a really important part of our week. And also,

00:20:40.219 --> 00:20:43.900
we have to archive a lot, because there's a lot of data that's generated all the time,

00:20:43.900 --> 00:20:50.540
so we're moving data around. Yeah, so that's, I don't know, I'm going to say that's a typical week.

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:51.579
Yeah, okay, we'll go with that.

00:20:52.219 --> 00:20:58.219
I think it's hard to define, it's hard to fit, you know, a week or a day in the life into a

00:20:58.219 --> 00:21:02.859
description, but it's so helpful for context, so I appreciate trying to squeeze it all in there.

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:08.540
And thank you, Natasha, for asking that question. There is another one in the Slido,

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:13.660
which has risen to the top from Abigail. Again, I see an asterisk, I'm going to read this for

